Want to Overcome Nerves?

Whether you are prepping for an Interview, a Presentation, or an Audition, those nerves can creep up.

I put out feelers in my mailing list recently as to what they would want to review in my next webinar and this was topic tied for first place!

Learn tips and tricks on how to overcome nerves.

tricks you can use:
- In Advance
- The Week Before
- The Day Of

This Wednesday, Feb 1st at 6pm ET. Recordings will not be sent out.

Link in bio to register.

Do you get nervous before a presentation or an interview? How about a nerve wracking audition for something you really want?

I get it. As an actor, I've been through the ringer of high pressure situations and I used to get NERVOUS. I would be completely fine one minute and then as soon as I walked in the room, my cheeks would twitch uncontrollably.

I started researching different ways to calm down my nervous system and a few years ago, started working with clients and classes on tips and tricks that worked.

I use my acting background to make these tips easy to digest and dare I say it... fun 😀

Tomorrow I'm hosting a free webinar all about Overcoming Nerves. 10 ways to overcome those uncontrollable nerves, or at least know exactly how to diminish them with practice.

My tips are split up into 3 categories:
⭐️ Things to do In Advance
⭐️ Things to do The Week Of
⭐️ Things to do The Day Of

Join me tomorrow at 6pm ET. Link in bio to Register 😀

Relaxed and excited 😀

It's how we want to feel before any public speaking engagement or interview.

⭐️ We want to feel prepared.

⭐️ We want to feel at ease with an audience.

⭐️ We want to feel focused and engaged.

⭐️ We want to feel on time, not rushed, and ready for any changes outside of our control.

And that's all possible.

This evening at 6pm ET, I am sharing tools to help get you into this place. Tools that can calm us down before stressful situations.

I divided this topic into 3 sections.

☀️ Things we can do IN ADVANCE

☀️ Things we can do THE WEEK BEFORE

☀️ Things we can do THE DAY OF

That even includes things we can do in the moment we are in the hot seat (or standing in front of a podium, you get it).

There are so many things out of our control... let's focus on all that we can do!

And remember, recordings won't be sent out after to the group. A video will be available to those in my membership.

I asked Todd Savvas a question I've struggled with. When you want something so bad but are so focused on the results that it blocks you from manifesting.

Todd absolutely delivered with advice that I've kept in mind for months. I share this note with everyone!

Ask yourself if you have it right now. If no, you're not allowed to think about it.

At times, when you're up for it, feel the excitement of having what you want. Enjoy it. Let that be enough.

For more tips on manifesting and getting what you want, as well as other tips and tricks from Spiritual Teacher Todd Savvas, check out the most recent episode of @mentorsonthemic podcast. Link in bio or where ever you listen to podcasts.

How do we detach from what we do?
For over achievers especially, this can feel impossible. It especially hits home when you are in between jobs or not doing what you want to be doing (yet!) As an actress, I GET THIS. I understand what it is to question whether I can even call myself an actress if I'm not currently acting in anything.
I'm so happy to have Kara Barnett back on the podcast. She fills us in on what's been going on since our last interview. Starting out as a casting associate producer on America’s Next Top Model, she worked consistently with companies and Networks such as Viacom, Discovery, CBS, BET, A&E, and OWN. We last saw her as Creative Manager of Strong Black Lead at Netflix.
Kara Barnett currently is a Senior Creative with the Apple TV+ Product and Design team. She also loves creating through her film production company of many years, 25EightProductions and has recently added a new agency arm to the company that focuses on short form content development and creation with Black and Brown brands and creators as well as experiential creative direction.
In this episode:

⭐️ We talk about where she was after leaving Netflix

⭐️ Leaning on her supportive network

⭐️ Attending a retreat called "Waking Hours" and shifting her perspective on how much time we have

⭐️ The importance of positive self talk

⭐️ Advice for talking to those affected by layoffs, more in this ⁠LinkedIn post⁠

While Kara is now a Senior Creative at Apple TV+, she now understands that she is so more than the place she attaches herself to or her job title, she invests in the brand that is Kara Inc. and all of the places she works gives more to her as a whole.
"You don’t have to rush to do anything, we will not forget you." - @createdby.kara

People always ask me what I've learned from Casting Directors about auditioning.

Even prior to interviewing Casting Directors on the podcast, I used to take workshops with CDs and I was a reader for various offices.

I always used to ask Casting Directors (and Agents) this question:

❓What do you see in the actors that book all of the time❓

There are some actors that always seem to be working. They must have uncovered some secret, right?

And this is what I would hear.

The actors that book all of the time always have an air of "I don't care if I book this." They obviously CARE. They memorized the lines, made choices, showed up on time, etc. But they had an air of 'Im fine if I book this or not.'

Our Mentor this week, Actress and Indie filmmaker @izzystevens talks a lot about getting to a place of f*** it energy, before booking a huge Netflix film. She was about to quit, become a director and filmmaker, leave acting behind her, but her agent said "just one more audition." And she booked it.

It's hard to get to that place. Actors: have you thought about this at all? Let me know in the comments below.

Debra Zane's credits include "The Hunger Games" franchise, "Oceans" franchise, "Catch me if You Can," "Dreamgirls," "Traffic," "The Planet of the Apes" franchise, and so many more.

Everything you do, no matter how mundane, can be met with intention.

If I get a haircut, I think about how I want to feel getting that haircut. Doesn't matter that I've had many, many, many haircuts in my life.

How can I show up differently to a hair cut, to an eye doctor's appointment, to meeting a friend?

Doesn't that change how you can look at the small things?

It's all about how I want to feel and how I show up for that.

Next daily task or monotonous to do, try entering that with a different, more positive intention. Maybe 📸 yourself getting that haircut or eating lunch in a different place or time. Who knows? Have fun with it.

There is SO much we can't share right now on social media during this strike.

We've gone over all we can't talk about on social media, but what can we talk about?!

I invited Social Media Strategist for Actors Heidi Dean on @mentorsonthemic podcast to discuss why this strike is the perfect way to get your social media in place!

Tip #1 - There is so much we can talk regarding the strike itself. Remember that a lot of your followers aren't actors. Inform your audience as to what is at stake. Don't forget to use strike related hashtags!

Tip #2 - There are SO many things we can still discuss right now that exclude bookings, film, and TV. Post about your day, industry news and trends, causes you believe in, special skills, etc. For more ideas from Heidi, listen to the this mini bonus episode of the podcast.

Tip #3 - Outside industry news. Besides acting, what else can you lean into? Hate to break it to you, but most of networking is whether a person connects with you outside of acting. Let people get to know you 😀 More suggestions for this on the podcast 🎙️

Listen to @marketing4actors talk about why this is the PERFECT time to set up your social media strategy. That way when you book that big project, you already have a fan base and strategy in place!

Full episode with more ideas wherever you listen to podcasts! Link in bio 😀

Social Media Strategist Heidi Dean shares her three tips for making any video go VIRAL.

⚡️ The first is your HOOK. Catching text or audio or something visual go get people to stay. Try DOUBLE HOOKS.

⚡️ Analyze your WATCH TIME. How long are people watching your video before cutting out? All of that affects the algorithm and whether Instagram chooses to share your video with more people. Did they watch it more than once? Heidi shared how some of her videos have 300% watch time.

⚡️ Lastly, viral videos often have a SPARK. Heidi defines this as an influential account seeing it, relating to it, and sharing it with their audience. Sometimes the spark is the video appearing on the explore page of IG... @itscourtneymichelle discusses this happening on some of her viral videos that were shared by Lena Dunham or Taika Waititi.

Heidi also reminds us that short form content is for people who DON'T KNOW US. That blew my mind.

For more from Heidi, check out the most recent episode of the podcast all about going viral. And why we shouldn't say "Hey Guys" at the top of the video. (I felt called out ☺️)
